In the first step, we will compare different types of clustering using the K-Means algorithm. The first approach focuses solely on numeric variables, comparing two scenarios: one using the raw data (excluding variables with high correlations) and another using the PCA components derived in the first part of the analysis.

For the second approach, K-Means will be applied to mixed data, combining both numeric and categorical variables.

Kmeans with PCA data

If we compare the graphs, there is stabilization between 5 and 7 clusters in the Silhouette method. Similarly, in the Elbow method, the slope becomes less steep around 5 and 7 clusters.

Between the cluster 3 and 1 is some elapsing data within the PC1 vs PC2. This also ocurre within the 1 and the 0 in the PC1 vs PC3. The other clusters all well separarted in the first factorial plane.

Inertia (WCSS): 469.44182341248046
Silhouette Score: 0.5704171764668877

If we use 5 cluster there's seem to be more clarity between the clusters. The silhouette is also almost over 0.5 and it visible in the graphs.

If we compare the information we can said that the best number of cluster for the PCA data is 7, but we decide to keep 5, because it does not make sense to have that amount of clusters when the sample is not that large.

The principal characteristics of the clusters are given in the next table. Where in the categorical variables we have the mode of the cluster, and in the end we have the proportion of the cluster that has sleep disorders.

  • In cluster 2 and 4 it is shown that there are more nurse females with overweight. Despite the fact that the cluster 0 has a good perception of their quality of sleep, it is shown that both clusters have the biggest % sleep disorder (over 90%). The differences between the 2 and 4 are the stress level,the quantity of daily steps and the age gith a avg. gap of almost 10 years.

  • Cluster 3 have the lowest proportions of sleep disorder, most of the members of this cluster are men, lawyers with a normal bmi.

In general it can be concluded that the perception of the sleep quality is not directly related with having or not a sleep disorder.

Kmeans with raw data

For this, we need data without strong correlations. The variables related to blood pressure have a high correlation of almost 0.97. To avoid losing any information, we decided to create a new variable called pulse pressure. Pulse pressure is calculated as the difference between systolic and diastolic blood pressure.

If you compare the two graphs, there is stabilization around 4 clusters in the Silhouette Score graph and a noticeable decrease in the slope (tangent) in the Elbow Method graph. However, using 5 clusters appears slightly better, as it balances both metrics.

Inertia (WCSS): 694.6414160666794
Silhouette Score: 0.57221538910709

Inertia (WCSS): 694.6414160666794
Silhouette Score: 0.57221538910709

There is a larger decrease in WCSS and a slight improvement in the Silhouette Score when choosing 5 clusters. Additionally, using pairplot to visualize the data reveals better separation of the clusters compared to 4 clusters. Choosing 5 clusters reduces overlaps between the groups, providing a more distinct and interpretable clustering structure.

The data description for the cluster is as follows.

  • Clusters 2 and 3 have the highest percentage of sleep disorders. Both groups are overweight, have higher levels of stress, and report the same perception of their sleep quality as being regular. They diverge in physical activity, with cluster 3 doing more than double the amount of cluster 2. There is also a difference in age, with an average gap of 10 years.

  • Clusters 0 and 4 are also very similar in terms of their sleep quality, weight (both are within the normal range), and stress levels. They have almost the same percentage of sleep disorders. The differences between these clusters are more related to their occupation, gender, and the average time spent doing physical activity.

  • Cluster 1 is very different, being composed primarily of male doctors who have lower levels of stress, high sleep quality, and almost no sleep disorders.

Kmeans with mixed data

For this, we will also use the pulse pressure variable and exclude the sleep disorder variable. This is because the sleep disorder variable is the target variable that this dataset aims to explain.

Now we have the assosiations between numerical and categorical variables finding some interesting relationships:

  • Age is highly associated with occupation, quality of sleep and stress level.
  • The hear rate is associated with quality of sleep, stress level and BMI category.
  • Other important relations are gender with occupation and sleep disorder with bmi category.

In this case the elbow method does not show a clear point where the trend of the line change, but the silhouette method suggest to take 6 or 8 clusters.

Inertia (WCSS): 654.0051973653807
Silhouette Score: 0.5304769553918965

Inertia (WCSS): 848.3962463374016
Silhouette Score: 0.45668915344071426

If we compared the silhouette score and the cost. The best quantity of cluster for the mixed kmeans is 8 clusters. But taking into account the size of the data base, we consider that 8 clusters are too much, so we decide to keep 6.

What we observed earlier about the positive association between BMI category and occupation with the presence of sleep disorders is reflected in clusters 0 and 1, where being overweight and working as a Nurse or Salesperson increase the likelihood of having a sleep disorder.

From cluster 4 and the association matrix, we can infer that the BMI category is the principal driver for the presence of sleep disorders.

  • Clusters 0 and 1 appear to be similar in that being overweight and having high levels of stress are related to sleep disorders. However, they diverge in the amount of physical activity performed.

  • Cluster 2 seems to show a relationship between age and being overweight. This is because, despite other characteristics, the perceived quality of sleep in this cluster is higher than in all the other clusters.

  • Clusters 4 and 5 diverge primarily in age, indicating that within the same amount of sleep, perceived quality of sleep, and stress levels, being younger makes one less prone to sleep disorders.

From the analysis, it is evident that overweight consistently appears as the most significant variable distinguishing the clusters. Across all clusters, individuals who are overweight exhibit higher levels of stress and a greater likelihood of experiencing sleep disorders. However, when comparing clusters that share overweight status, differences arise in age and the amount of physical activity, indicating that these variables further refine the observed patterns. K-Means with Raw Data and K-Means with PCA achieved the same silhouette score (0.57), indicating that both models performed equally well in terms of clustering quality.

The raw data model is preferable because it retains the original features, making the clusters easier to interpret without the added complexity of principal components.

  • The PCA model, while computationally efficient, reduces dimensionality, which can lead to a loss of interpretability.

  • The K-Means with Mixed Data model performed slightly worse, with a silhouette score of 0.53. This suggests that the inclusion of categorical variables (even after removing correlations) did not meaningfully improve clustering and may have introduced additional noise or complexity.

Given the results, the K-Means with Raw Data model is the best choice. It balances clustering performance (silhouette score of 0.57) with interpretability, as it retains the original features. While the mixed data model attempts to incorporate categorical variables, its lower silhouette score indicates that the numerical features alone already capture most of the relevant variance.

This analysis highlights that addressing overweight status, stress management, and encouraging physical activity could be key strategies for improving sleep quality across the clusters.
